==================== KAFKA FLOW – IVR SYSTEM (COMPLETE END-TO-END) ====================

SYSTEM CONTEXT

Microservices:
- api-gateway
- ivr-orchestrator-service
- customer-service
- policy-service
- claims-service (Kafka Producer)
- notification-service (Kafka Consumer)

Kafka is used ONLY between:
claims-service → notification-service

Kafka is NOT used for:
- customer lookup
- policy retrieval
- orchestrator communication


=======================================================================================

ENTRY FLOW (SYNCHRONOUS PART)

1. User initiates IVR request
2. API Gateway receives request
3. API Gateway routes to ivr-orchestrator-service
4. Orchestrator performs synchronous calls:
   - customer-service (fetch customer details)
   - policy-service (fetch policy details)
   - claims-service (create/update claim)

At this point, Kafka is NOT involved


=======================================================================================

KAFKA ENTRY POINT (TRANSITION FROM SYNC → ASYNC)

Kafka starts ONLY AFTER:
- claims-service completes business logic
- an event needs to be emitted (side-effect)

Trigger events:
- CLAIM_CREATED
- CLAIM_STATUS_UPDATED


=======================================================================================

EVENT GENERATION (CLAIMS-SERVICE)

Flow inside claims-service:

1. Request received from orchestrator
2. Business logic executes (claim creation/update)
3. System prepares event payload

Event structure:
- eventType (CLAIM_CREATED / CLAIM_STATUS_UPDATED)
- claimId
- customerId
- status

4. Event handed over to Kafka Producer


=======================================================================================

PRODUCER FLOW (CLAIMS-SERVICE → KAFKA)

1. Producer sends message to Kafka topic

Topic:
- claims-events

Key:
- claimId

2. Kafka determines partition using key

Partition strategy:
- Same claimId → same partition
- Ensures ordering per claim

Example:
- claimId=123 → Partition 1
- claimId=456 → Partition 2


=======================================================================================

MESSAGE STORAGE IN KAFKA

Kafka stores messages as:

Topic: claims-events
Partitions: multiple
Offsets: sequential per partition

Example:

Partition 1:
Offset 0 → CLAIM_CREATED
Offset 1 → CLAIM_STATUS_UPDATED

Partition 2:
Offset 0 → CLAIM_CREATED


=======================================================================================

CONSUMER ENTRY (NOTIFICATION-SERVICE)

Consumer subscribes to:

- Topic: claims-events
- Consumer Group: notification-group


=======================================================================================

CONSUMER GROUP BEHAVIOR

If multiple instances exist:

- Instance 1 → Partition 0
- Instance 2 → Partition 1
- Instance 3 → Partition 2

Rule:
- One partition is consumed by only one consumer within a group

Scaling:
- Increase partitions → increase parallel processing
- Increase consumers → distribute load


=======================================================================================

MESSAGE CONSUMPTION FLOW

1. Consumer polls message from Kafka
2. Reads event payload
3. Identifies eventType

Routing logic:

- CLAIM_CREATED → trigger SMS notification
- CLAIM_STATUS_UPDATED → trigger Email notification


=======================================================================================

OFFSET MANAGEMENT (CRITICAL)

Offset = position of message in partition

Configuration:
- enable.auto.commit = false (manual commit)

Flow:

1. Consumer reads message at offset X
2. Processes message (notification logic)
3. If success → commit offset
4. If failure → do NOT commit


=======================================================================================

SUCCESS FLOW

- Message read
- Notification sent successfully
- Offset committed

Result:
- Kafka marks message as processed
- Message will NOT be re-delivered


=======================================================================================

FAILURE FLOW

CASE 1: Failure BEFORE offset commit

- Message read
- Processing fails
- Offset NOT committed

Result:
- Kafka re-delivers same message
- No data loss
- Possible duplicate processing


CASE 2: Failure AFTER offset commit (BAD DESIGN)

- Offset committed early
- Processing fails

Result:
- Message lost permanently
- Data inconsistency


=======================================================================================

IDEMPOTENCY HANDLING

Problem:
- Same event may be processed multiple times

Solution:

- Use unique key:
  claimId + eventType

- Maintain processed_events store

Flow:

1. Before processing → check if event already processed
2. If yes → skip
3. If no → process and store record


=======================================================================================

RETRY MECHANISM

On failure:

1. Consumer retries processing (configured attempts)
2. Retry can be immediate or with backoff
3. If success → commit offset
4. If still fails → move to DLQ


=======================================================================================

DEAD LETTER QUEUE (DLQ)

DLQ Topic:
- claims-events-dlq

Usage:
- Store failed messages after retries

Purpose:
- Debugging
- Manual reprocessing
- Failure analysis


=======================================================================================

REBALANCING SCENARIO

Triggered when:
- New consumer instance joins
- Existing consumer crashes

Effect:
- Kafka redistributes partitions among consumers

Impact:
- Temporary pause in consumption
- Possible duplicate processing

Handled by:
- Idempotency logic


